# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cucumber-bdd
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] BDD involves use of a domain-specific language (DSL) using natural-language constructs (e.g., English-like sentences) that can express the behavior and the expected outcomes.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] BDD encourages collaboration among developers, quality assurance experts, and customer representatives in a software project.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] It encourages teams to use conversation and concrete examples to formalize a shared understanding of how the application should behave.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] BDD is considered an effective practice especially when the *problem space* is complex.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] A common misconception regarding BDD is that it supposedly is a refinement of test-driven development (TDD).
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] While it was originally derived from TDD practices, the sole purpose of BDD is to gain a *shared understanding* of the problem space and find a way to write this down in a Business Language, using Real data, whilst being Intention revealing, Essential and Focused (BRIEF).
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] BDD combines the techniques of TDD with ideas from domain-driven design and object-oriented analysis and design to provide software development and management teams with shared tools and a shared process to collaborate on software development.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] At a high level, BDD is an idea about how software development should be managed by both business interests and technical insight.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] Its *practice* involves use of specialized tools.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] Some tools specifically for BDD can be used for TDD.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] The tools automate the ubiquitous language.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] BDD is a process by which DSL structured natural-language statements are converted into executable tests.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] The result is executable specification eventually forming Living Documentation: Requirements that are also the first acceptance tests that drive your software development (Acceptance test-driven development).
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] Starting from this point, many people developed BDD frameworks over a period of years, finally framing it in terms of a communication and collaboration framework for developers, QA and non-technical or business participants in a software project.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] BDD suggests that software tests should be named in terms of desired *behavior*.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] Borrowing from agile software development the "desired behavior" in this case consists of the requirements set by the business — that is, the desired behavior that has business value for whatever entity commissioned the software unit under construction.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] Within BDD practice, this is referred to as BDD being an "outside-in" activity.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] TDD does not differentiate tests in terms of high-level software requirements, low-level technical details or anything in between.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] One way of looking at BDD therefore, is that it is an evolution of TDD which makes more specific choices.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] Another BDD suggestion relates to *how* the desired behavior should be specified.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] BDD suggests using a semi-formal format for behavioral specification which is borrowed from user story specifications from the field of object-oriented analysis and design.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] The scenario aspect of this format may be regarded as an application of Hoare logic to behavioral specification of software using the domain-specific language.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] BDD suggests that business analysts and software developers should collaborate in this area and should specify behavior in terms of user stories, which are each explicitly documented.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] BDD does not require how this information is formatted, but it does suggest that a team should decide on a relatively simple, standardized format with the above elements.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] It also suggests that the scenarios should be phrased declaratively rather than imperatively — in the business language, with no reference to elements of the UI through which the interactions take place.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] This format is referred to in Cucumber as the Gherkin language.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] BDD borrows the concept of the *ubiquitous language* from domain driven design.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] A ubiquitous language is a (semi-)formal language that is shared by all members of a software development team — both software developers and non-technical personnel.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] The language in question is both used and developed by all team members as a common means of discussing the domain of the software in question.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] In this way BDD becomes a vehicle for communication between all the different roles in a software project.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] A common risk with software development includes communication breakdowns between Developers and Business Stakeholders.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] BDD uses the specification of desired behavior as a ubiquitous language for the project Team members.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] This is the reason that BDD insists on a semi-formal language for behavioral specification: some formality is a requirement for being a ubiquitous language.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] In addition, having such a ubiquitous language creates a domain model of specifications, so that specifications may be reasoned about formally.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] This model is also the basis for the different BDD-supporting software tools that are available.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] The example given above establishes a user story for a software system under development.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] This user story identifies a stakeholder, a business effect and a business value.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] It also describes several scenarios, each with a precondition, trigger and expected outcome.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] Each of these parts is exactly identified by the more formal part of the language (the term **Given** might be considered a keyword, for example) and may therefore be processed in some way by a tool that understands the formal parts of the ubiquitous language.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] Most BDD applications use text-based DSLs and specification approaches.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] However, graphical modeling of integration scenarios has also been applied successfully in practice, e.g., for testing purposes.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] Much like TDD, BDD may involve using specialized tooling.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] BDD requires not only test code as does TDD, but also a document that describes behavior in a more human-readable language.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] This requires a two-step process for executing the tests, reading and parsing the descriptions, and reading the test code and finding the corresponding test implementation to execute.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] This process makes BDD more laborious for developers.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] Proponents suggest that due to its human-readable nature the value of those documents extends to a relatively non-technical audience, and can hence serve as a communication means for describing requirements ("features").
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] In principle, a BDD support tool is a testing framework for software, much like the tools that support TDD.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] However, where TDD tools tend to be quite free-format in what is allowed for specifying tests, BDD tools are linked to the definition of the ubiquitous language.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] The ubiquitous language allows business analysts to document behavioral requirements in a way that will also be understood by developers.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] The principle of BDD support tooling is to make these same requirements documents directly executable as a collection of tests.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] If this cannot be achieved because of reasons related to the technical tool that enables the execution of the specifications, then either the style of writing the behavioral requirements must be altered or the tool must be changed.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] A separate subcategory of behavior-driven development is formed by tools that use specifications as an input language rather than user stories.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] Specification tools don't use user stories as an input format for test scenarios but rather use functional specifications for units that are being tested.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] These specifications often have a more technical nature than user stories and are usually less convenient for communication with business personnel than are user stories.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] Such a specification may exactly specify the behavior of the component being tested, but is less meaningful to a business user.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] As a result, specification-based testing is seen in BDD practice as a complement to story-based testing and operates at a lower level.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] Specification testing is often seen as a replacement for free-format unit testing.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] The "three amigos", also referred to as a "Specification Workshop", is a meeting where the product owner discusses the requirement in the form of specification by example with different stakeholders like the QA and development team.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] The key goal for this discussion is to trigger conversation and identify any missing specifications.
[src:cucumber-bdd/behavior-driven-development] The discussion also gives a platform for QA, development team and product owner to converge and hear out each other's perspective to enrich the requirement and also make sure if they are building the right product.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] Cucumber was originally written in the Ruby programming language and was originally used exclusively for Ruby testing as a complement to the RSpec BDD framework.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] Cucumber now supports a variety of different programming languages through various implementations, including Java and JavaScript.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] There is a port of Cucumber to .NET called SpecFlow, now superseded by Reqnroll.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] Gherkin is the language that Cucumber uses to define test cases.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] It is designed to be non-technical and human readable, and collectively describes use cases relating to a software system.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] The purpose behind Gherkin's syntax is to promote behavior-driven development practices across an entire development team, including business analysts and managers.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] It seeks to enforce firm, unambiguous requirements starting in the initial phases of requirements definition by business management and in other stages of the development lifecycle.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] In addition to providing a script for automated testing, Gherkin's natural language syntax is designed to provide simple documentation of the code under test.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] Gherkin currently supports keywords in dozens of languages.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] Syntax is centered around a line-oriented design, similar to that of Python.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] The structure of a file is defined using whitespace and other control characters.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] Lines starting with `#` are considered comments, and can be placed anywhere in a file.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] Instructions are any non-empty and non-comment line.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] They consist of a recognized Gherkin keyword followed by a string.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] All Gherkin files have the `.feature` file extension.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] They contain a single Feature definition for the system under test and are an executable test script.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] Cucumber comes with a built-in command line interface that covers a comprehensive list of instructions.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] Like most command line tools, cucumber provides the `--help` option that provides a summary of arguments the command accepts.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] Cucumber command line can be used to quickly run defined tests.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] It also supports running a subset of scenarios by filtering tags.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] The above command helps in executing only those scenarios that have the specified `@tag-name`.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] Arguments can be provided as a logical `OR` or `AND` operation of tags.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] Apart from tags, scenarios can be filtered on scenario names.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] The above command will run only those scenarios that contain the word 'logout'.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] It is also useful to be able to know what went wrong when a test fails.
[src:cucumber-bdd/cucumber-software] Cucumber makes it easy to catch bugs in the code with the `--backtrace` option.
[src:cucumber-bdd/gherkin] In order to allow Gherkin to be written in a number of languages, the keywords have been translated into multiple languages.
[src:cucumber-bdd/gherkin] To improve readability and flow, some languages may have more than one translation for any given keyword.
[src:cucumber-bdd/gherkin] You can have all of your step definitions in one file, or in multiple files.
[src:cucumber-bdd/gherkin] When you start with your project, all your step definitions will probably be in one file.
[src:cucumber-bdd/installation] Cucumber is available for most mainstream programming languages.
[src:cucumber-bdd/installation] We recommend choosing an implementation for the same platform or programming language as the production code.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] Automation provides many benefits over manual testing.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] For API testing, tests drive the SUT via its application programming interface (API).
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] Compared to manual testing, automated API testing often can execute a relatively large number of cases in a relatively short time.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] For GUI testing, tests drive the SUT via its graphical user interface (GUI) by generating events such as keystrokes and mouse clicks.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] Automated GUI testing can be challenging to develop, but can run much faster than a human could perform the same testing.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] When automated testing is in place, regression testing can be a relatively quick and easy operation.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] Instead of a significant outlay of human time and effort, a regression test run could require nothing more than a push of a button and even starting the run can be automated.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] The following are notable testing techniques categorized as test automation.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to assess the business risk of releasing the SUT.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] The scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] For model-based testing, the SUT is modeled and test cases can be generated from it to support no code test development.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] Some tools support the encoding of test cases as plain English that can be used on multiple operating systems, browsers, and smart devices.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] Test-driven development (TDD) inherently includes the generation of automation test code.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] Unit test code is written while the SUT code is written.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] When the code is complete, the tests are complete as well.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] A review of 52 practitioner and 26 academic sources found that five main factors to consider in test automation decision are: system under test (SUT), scope of testing, test toolset, human and organizational topics, cross-cutting factors.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] The factors most frequently identified were: need for regression testing, economic factors, and maturity of SUT.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] While the reusability of automated tests is valued by software development companies, this property can also be viewed as a disadvantage as it leads to a plateau effect, where repeatedly executing the same tests stops detecting errors.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] Testing tools can help automate tasks such as product installation, test data creation, GUI interaction, problem detection (consider parsing or polling agents equipped with test oracles), defect logging, etc., without necessarily automating tests in an end-to-end fashion.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] To support coded automated testing, the test engineer or software quality assurance person must have software coding ability.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] Some testing techniques such as table-driven and no-code can lessen or alleviate the need for programming skill.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] A test automation framework provides a programming environment that integrates test logic, test data, and other resources.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] The framework provides the basis of test automation and simplifies the automation effort.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] Using a framework can lower the cost of test development and maintenance.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] If there is change to any test case then only the test case file needs to be updated and the driver script and startup script will remain the same.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] A framework is responsible for defining the format in which to express expectations, providing a mechanism to hook into or drive the SUT, executing the tests, and reporting results.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] A test automation interface is a platform that provides a workspace for incorporating multiple testing tools and frameworks for system/integration testing.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] A test automation interface may simplify the process of mapping tests to business criteria without coding.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] A test automation interface may improve the efficiency and flexibility of maintaining tests.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] The parser is present to parse the object files coming from the object repository into the test specific scripting language.
[src:cucumber-bdd/test-automation] Collection of UI/Application object data recorded by the testing tool while exploring the SUT.
